RT @evanbirdarts: I hate to ask for help 😭 But my void son Zaki is getting sicker, weaker and thinner by day (right pic ;_;). I took him to…
anyway yay therapy.

I'm just tired and I resent it when a social problem's solution involves me doing all the work because I feel like I've already done that enough, but also, it doesn't work like that so that reaction doesn't help.
idk I had a review meeting with my therapist today so I guess a lot of this shit is on my mind.

like an acquaintance giving you condolences about a stressful thing and saying "let me know if I can do anything to help" and you know you'll never call that person at 2am to cry about your breakup so it's just a platitude, a social interaction balm that soothes just a little.
"tell me what I can do to help you with your depression and anxiety or anything like that" isn't a request she wants me to answer honestly. she says it because it feels right to say.

she has to decide if she wants to change how she communicates and no matter how much I wish for it, we're not going to have that heart-to-heart where I tell her all the things that would help me and she takes it all to heart and starts doing those things. it's not gonna happen.

fair? not really but also not the point. these arguments that spin off from these things make me utterly miserable and I need to avoid getting mired in one when I have a map already that tells me "this way lies swamps of suffering" when I start down that path.

idk I just. I need to accept that she's going to get defensive when I suggest something that would smooth over something in our communication, and I need to work on how to not flare up in annoyance when it inevitably happens.

to me, that sounded like "what are you doing that is causing other people to bully you" and it made me shut up and stop sharing anything like that. and so she assumed the bullying stopped, and I assumed I'd be blamed for things that went wrong. STILL untangling that in therapy.

it's a major difference in communication styles and it's long running. like when I'd get bullied in school and upon telling her she'd try to find a way to lessen the impact of it by asking if I might be doing anything that was getting their attention.

she gets defensive about anything that seems to hint she is doing parenting wrong (when it's not even that, it's two adults who share living space interacting) and she never sees those requests of mine as reasonable.

the thing that sucks is that I want to have a heart to heart about how it would help me so much if she tried sanding some edges off the way she talks to me I'd have an easier time not feeling immediately defensive, but I'm not going to get it.

or she goes silent and then goes "you're just too sensitive and you have all these rules for how to talk to you, I'm never going to keep this straight and you know it" and then I feel like I'm being told a small thing that would flag a conversation friendlier for me is Too Much

I say "hey it might help me feel like you're not totally tuning me out if you said something like 'hang on a sec' before you ask whatever it is, think you could try that?" and she goes silent and if I again nudge for the answer I want she gets snappy at me

me: "mom I just wanted you to let me know if that was going to be a problem if I wait until afternoon to get your prescriptions to save a trip, or is there something you need for morning?"
mom: "it's fine! I would have told you if it wasn't!"

she does legit have some hearing issues, not major but she has a hard time when the TV is on (which is...all the time that she's awake) so I'll ask if she heard me and she gets all huffy and "YES, I DID hear you, what about it??"

like, me: "mom I have a psychiatrist appointment tomorrow at 2, I plan to go get your prescriptions after that since I'll have refills too, okay?"
mom: "get me a glass of water hon"

ughhh I need to stop getting so annoyed about this stupid thing. I will say something to mom that requires an answer or acknowledgement, but when she starts talking she makes a totally unrelated request of me and does not follow up on what I said.

Spelling Hawaiian words properly is a very basic step in showing respect to the language. ʻŌlelo Hawaiʻi is an endangered language, and ʻŌlelo Hawaiʻi Month is a great time to learn more about it and the efforts to restore it.
https://t.co/dJTtD1d0OW
The kahakō is a macron, or mark for indicating a longer vowel/stress on a vowel. A little harder to access on typical keyboards, but your phone should make it easier to add!
The ‘okina looks like (but is not) an apostrophe and is an important part of spelling Hawaiian words. It's a glottal stop, like the sound in the middle of "oh-oh." Spell it properly: Hawai‘i!

RT @ErikNYCSWE: Dark-eyed Junco (f+m) in deep snow, looking for something to eat. #Birdcpp https://t.co/J0UaZOSsnw

but in the PL:A setting, people don't have close contact with Pokemon. there's a lot of misconceptions. every little bit of info is important. completing the Pokedex feels like a real objective, not just "the necessary work to earn the shiny charm" or "because plot said so"

so to me this feels very satisfying, like I am actually gaining useful information. I never really had the feeling in the other games that I, the player character, was making groundbreaking discoveries from catching one Wurmple. It felt like a lot of this info was already known.

in PL:A, what you have instead is a notebook, and you need to record more information than can be gained from catching just one. size differences, form differences, attacks used, time of day encountered, etc- now /this/ feels like fieldwork.

so the thing I'm enjoying about Pokemon Legends: Arceus is that it actually feels like doing fieldwork. "catch one Pokemon and the Pokedex has all pertinent information about it in modern setting game" is a game mechanic that works well enough, but it's not terribly satisfying.

RT @sarahhartshorne: If you are feeling enraged/overwhelmed by the news in Texas, here’s some do’s and don’ts from me, who is not an expert…

I know, weather alerts go out all the time where you barely see any weather from it. But this is why Emergency and Particularly Dangerous Situation warnings are issued. If you pay attention to any, pay attention to these.

If you EVER hear a weather alert for your area that includes the words “emergency” or “particularly dangerous situation” PLEASE take it seriously. These are issued for severe thunderstorms, tornadoes, and flooding that are life-threatening to a densely populated area.

A flash flood emergency is worse than a flash flood warning. It means that life-threatening flooding that requires water rescues is expected or underway, or that the area affected is highly populated and expects to see flooding likely to cause loss of life or property.
